1043
01:58:13,983 --> 01:58:15,464
Let's be totally blunt about that.

1044
01:58:15,664 --> 01:58:18,386
But he's a journalist, as I say, at the posh end of journalism.

1045
01:58:19,147 --> 01:58:24,550
The New Yorker asked him to report on Donald Trump as he was then a candidate.

1046
01:58:25,231 --> 01:58:35,218
He told me that he set off on the US publicity trail for this book, however, just after Donald Trump had entered the White House, with some claim to be a bit of an expert, of course, on Donald Trump.

1047
01:58:35,578 --> 01:58:48,996
and he told me that the, broadly speaking, unhappy young people, unhappy with the arrival of Donald Trump in the White House, actually found some kind of succour, some kind of comfort in discussing with him his new book and talking about it.

1048
01:58:49,568 --> 01:58:51,709
And we did 28 cities in 30 days.

1049
01:58:52,149 --> 01:58:59,033
And it was so therapeutic for me, you know, to get in front of a crowd of, my audience skews a little young in the States, so kind of heartbroken young people.

1050
01:58:59,133 --> 01:59:01,675
And we just talked it out, you know, during the readings.

1051
01:59:01,775 --> 01:59:08,879
And I thought it was really wonderful to have Lincoln in our minds, but also to have a work of art that was weird and strange and hard.

1052
01:59:09,019 --> 01:59:10,280
It was refreshing for me to have done it.

1053
01:59:10,360 --> 01:59:12,181
And I think it was refreshing for us to talk about that.

1054
01:59:13,055 --> 01:59:15,457
Now, Vincent, you've read the book, I presume.

1055
01:59:15,737 --> 01:59:17,199
OK, is it good?

1056
01:59:17,319 --> 01:59:18,159
Would you like it?

1057
01:59:18,299 --> 01:59:22,163
I mean, ridiculous question, but you've read it, and I think you're probably the only one in the studio who has.

1058
01:59:22,403 --> 01:59:24,265
No, no, no, it's a perfectly fair question.

1059
01:59:24,345 --> 01:59:29,429
And not everything I read for The Man Booker, or whatever the topic of the day may be, I really love.

1060
01:59:30,410 --> 01:59:31,831
Actually, George Sanders said something

1061
01:59:32,111 --> 01:59:52,389
absolutely honest I think he's terribly nice guy terribly honest guy in his press conference he said lots of people have been telling him they get to page 30 or so and then think they can't take not the topic but the way it's written and it's written in a strange way a very very short paragraphs not entirely but as I flick through in this not radiophonic way you see it's written in

1062
01:59:53,470 --> 02:00:10,398
paragraphs of two three sentences he told me he was slightly influenced by thinking about Twitter and he's been trying to write like this for a while so if you can get past that and I have to say I did have to force myself sometimes you know it's nice if you have to read a novel for work you don't have any alternative so you've got to get on with it

1063
02:00:10,638 --> 02:00:14,480
And I would say, to be honest, about 50 pages in, I began to click with it.

1064
02:00:14,801 --> 02:00:18,563
And the underlying story is deeply emotional and very engrossing.

1065
02:00:18,823 --> 02:00:22,885
And strangely enough, there is, well, maybe not strangely enough, there is talk of a film.

1066
02:00:23,226 --> 02:00:25,247
I actually think it would make a magnificent play.

1067
02:00:25,267 --> 02:00:29,029
Because it's a bit like dialogue, as well as being a bit like Twitter.

1068
02:00:29,349 --> 02:00:33,592
But actually, he's taken an option, so to speak, on his own novel.

1069
02:00:33,952 --> 02:00:36,774
And they're now trying to turn it into a movie.

1070
02:00:37,654 --> 02:00:41,216
Well, we do happen to have a real live Texan in the studio, at no extra expense.

1071
02:00:41,256 --> 02:00:43,877
So, Andy, first of all, I mean, you haven't read this, have you?

1072
02:00:43,897 --> 02:00:44,077
No, no.

1073
02:00:44,417 --> 02:00:46,658
But we're talking about this as if it really matters.

1074
02:00:46,698 --> 02:00:49,920
I mean, does the Man Booker Prize matter in America?

1075
02:00:50,320 --> 02:00:53,261
No, that's an exactly right question.

1076
02:00:53,581 --> 02:00:55,482
And I can't claim George Sanders.

1077
02:00:55,602 --> 02:00:57,683
He's an Amarillo, which is kind of up in the panhandle.

1078
02:00:57,743 --> 02:00:58,763
I'm from Fort Worth.

1079
02:00:59,284 --> 02:01:00,224
But he's a Texan.

1080
02:01:00,244 --> 02:01:00,564
That's great.

1081
02:01:02,285 --> 02:01:12,988
When I heard about this, and when I heard we were going to be talking about it, I texted my brother about eight times, and I said, hey, Joe, does this lead you to reading it as an English teacher?

1082
02:01:13,188 --> 02:01:15,469
He teaches ninth graders English in America.

1083
02:01:15,509 --> 02:01:17,689
I said, does it lead your kids to buy the book?

1084
02:01:17,809 --> 02:01:21,631
Does it mean that Saunders Sales will grow in the United States?

1085
02:01:22,491 --> 02:01:26,392
He said, look, the sticker on the book makes everyone want to read it.

1086
02:01:26,892 --> 02:01:28,234
Really, that actually does make a difference.

1087
02:01:28,254 --> 02:01:28,996
That's what my brothers told me.

1088
02:01:29,036 --> 02:01:35,066
So I said, okay, sort of my follow up to my brother, does it mean anything for English teachers?

1089
02:01:35,106 --> 02:01:38,952
Does it mean that you're actually going to change your reading list based on a prize?

1090
02:01:39,943 --> 02:01:42,845
He said no.

1091
02:01:42,925 --> 02:01:48,888
So they're not going to get, Saunders isn't going to get contracts with schools necessarily, certainly not next year or in a couple of years.

1092
02:01:49,428 --> 02:01:50,209
But it'll help his sales.

1093
02:01:50,489 --> 02:01:51,149
Oh, without a doubt.

1094
02:01:51,670 --> 02:01:52,310
And I think you're right.

1095
02:01:52,330 --> 02:01:57,573
I think you see, I mean, you see the different sort of stickers on the books and it's like, oh, this won an award.

1096
02:01:57,633 --> 02:01:58,714
It's probably pretty good.

1097
02:01:58,814 --> 02:02:02,116
And Man Booker certainly has a reputation in the U.S.

1098
02:02:02,256 --> 02:02:06,558
Well, Simon, does it have a reputation in Singapore or around where you hang around in Asia?

1099
02:02:06,578 --> 02:02:09,100
I mean, do people, are people impressed at all by these kind of things?

1100
02:02:10,695 --> 02:02:14,279
I don't think that's a topic that's going to come up very much today, I'm sorry to say.

1101
02:02:15,280 --> 02:02:22,128
And I have to confess, I haven't read the book either, although it does actually look very interesting, and it looks very contemporary too.

1102
02:02:22,689 --> 02:02:30,878
But would booksellers, you know, you go into a bookshop in Singapore, would you see plastered over it, Man Booker, and would people read it, buy it on that basis, do you think?

1103
02:02:32,029 --> 02:02:35,754
A small number would, I mean the story of bookshops in Singapore is not a happy one.

1104
02:02:36,875 --> 02:02:40,080
You know, the largest and best bookshop closed down some years ago.

1105
02:02:40,120 --> 02:02:45,787
We've only really got one bookshop of any size, which is an English bookshop, which in a country of six million people is a bit sad.

1106
02:02:46,448 --> 02:02:47,709
That's surprising, isn't it, really?

1107
02:02:47,849 --> 02:02:56,853
But, I mean, given, obviously, it's a Commonwealth, well, it's recognised by a lot of Commonwealth authors, you might think, perhaps, that it's more impressive in that sort of way, but perhaps not.

1108
02:02:57,973 --> 02:02:59,714
Actually, it's an interesting thing in this.

1109
02:02:59,754 --> 02:03:06,697
Let me come back to you on this, Vincent, because this is a prize that has been opened up to Americans, as we said, only very recently, and they are dominating it.

1110
02:03:06,837 --> 02:03:07,497
Is that a problem?

1111
02:03:08,078 --> 02:03:11,400
Three out of six this year are American.

1112
02:03:11,860 --> 02:03:13,080
It's a huge industry.

1113
02:03:13,221 --> 02:03:14,841
It sells an enormous amount of books.

1114
02:03:15,742 --> 02:03:27,969
And also, it indicates the way that I think the book industry is going, that titles and prizes mean an awful lot, especially as people are buying on, let's be honest, Amazon and that kind of thing.

1115
02:03:28,209 --> 02:03:30,090
These kind of labels do help.

1116
02:03:30,310 --> 02:03:30,810
make a difference.

1117
02:03:30,830 --> 02:03:31,330
Well, there we are.

1118
02:03:31,931 --> 02:03:32,771
It's a good book.

1119
02:03:32,831 --> 02:03:33,351
We've said that.

1120
02:03:33,371 --> 02:03:35,392
We've got the authentication for that from Vincent.

1121
02:03:35,692 --> 02:03:37,113
It's sitting on the desk in front of him there.

1122
02:03:37,553 --> 02:03:38,454
I'm going to have a go.

